            "id": "999538815d6447b69a5bb",
            "questionText": "During an earthquake, $!$P$!$-waves travel through the Earth's crust. Consider a $!$P$!$-wave traveling through a granite layer with a frequency of $!$25~\\text{Hz}$!$ and a wavelength of $!$250~\\text{m}$!$. The wave then enters a different rock layer where its speed changes to $!$7500~\\text{m/s}$!$. Calculate the new wavelength of the $!$P$!$-wave in the second rock layer.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "7f6a264742d0400bb94e8",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the wave equation that links wave speed, frequency, and wavelength. Please select the correct equation.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e2484863-f982-4229-94d2-b6df0b9b92ca"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = f \\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\lambda / f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = \\lambda / v$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "96531e9e1cd449cea6622",
                    "stepText": "Great, now consider what property remains unchanged when the $!$P$!$-wave passes from one rock layer to another. Choose the correct invariant property.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "91d66318-1623-4c88-b48c-56e3cfc2c189"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "Frequency remains constant",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "Wavelength remains constant",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "Both frequency and wavelength change",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "a98beca7d6e14cd59b20e",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have selected the correct equation and identified the constant property, use the equation $!$v = f \\lambda$!$ to calculate the new wavelength. Substitute the new speed ($!$7500~\\text{m/s}$!$) and the constant frequency ($!$25~\\text{Hz}$!$) into the equation, and solve for the wavelength.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "300"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e2484863-f982-4229-94d2-b6df0b9b92ca",
                        "91d66318-1623-4c88-b48c-56e3cfc2c189"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
